To obtain the zeroth-order one-loop effective Lagrangian ${\cal L}^{(1)}_0$ indicated in the first equation of (\ref{L0L1L2}), we must perform the $p$-integration which can be handled by \cite{Brw-Dff,Rodf-Diss}
\begin{eqnarray}
\int d^Dp e^{Q\cdotp+\frac{1}{2}p\cdot R\cdot p} = \pi^{D/2}
 \mathrm{exp} \left[-\frac{1}{2} Q\cdot R^{-1}\cdot Q -\mathrm{tr}\frac{1}{2}\ln \left(-\frac{R}{2s}\right)\right].
\end{eqnarray}
